WEBVTT

00:00:01.300 --> 00:00:05.000
So, I'm going to talk about DIP PLC

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.740
, which has a few sort of slightly surprising properties to it

00:00:08.740 --> 00:00:09.180
.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:11.170
It's a slightly confusing system.

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:13.760
What does it mean?

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:18.510
A self-authenticating decentralized identifier, which is strongly

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:22.050
consistent, recoverable, and has key rotation.

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:23.850
Okay, so four things.

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:27.910
Strongly consistent, recoverable, self-authenticating

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:29.540
, and key rotation.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.450
And the slightly weird thing about this is, it does have

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:36.310
all these properties, but not all at the same time.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:39.700
As far as I'm aware, it's technically impossible to

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:41.450
have all these properties at the same time.

00:00:41.450 --> 00:00:42.360
Let me explain what I mean.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:45.960
So, what do we mean when we say self-auth

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:46.750
enticating?

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:49.010
We mean that you can look at the data, and you

00:00:49.010 --> 00:00:52.300
can confirm it's valid without looking at anything else.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:55.130
Okay, so the classic example is an IPFS document.

00:00:55.130 --> 00:00:59.490
If you have the ID of an IPFS document, that

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:00.430
is a hash.

00:01:00.580 --> 00:01:02.360
So, if somebody you don't trust it gives you the

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:05.060
document, you can then recreate that hash and make sure that

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:06.800
it's correct.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:07.840
Okay?

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:09.790
So, how does this look in DIP PLC?

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:14.240
Well, when you first create a new account in DIP

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:17.840
PLC, it's exactly like that, right?

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:21.780
So, for your first account, you make a document.

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:24.380
You put in, for example, your blue sky handle,

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:26.790
your PDS, a load of other stuff, and you

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:29.180
put in the key that's going to control this account.

00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:32.240
This is called the rotation key, and you take the hash

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:35.280
of this document, and that hashes your ID.

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:35.860
Okay?

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:38.790
So, this is exactly like IPFS, self-auth

00:01:38.790 --> 00:01:40.530
enticating content address.

00:01:40.530 --> 00:01:42.860
Then, if you want to make a change, what we

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:45.540
're going to do is we're going to replace maybe one

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:47.900
of the, maybe replace the handle, replace one of the

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:49.980
fields in there, and then we're going to sign it

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.810
with the key that we stated in that previous update.

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:53.540
Okay?

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:56.550
So, this is also cryptographically verifiable.

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:58.630
This is also basically self-authenticating, assuming you

00:01:58.630 --> 00:01:59.700
've got the whole chain.

00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:03.530
If I want to check this, I can check the signature

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:05.300
on this second one.

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:08.490
I can then check that it matches the key in the first

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:10.720
one, and then I can check the hash of the first

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:11.140
one.

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:13.230
So, I can authenticate the whole chain.

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:14.510
I don't need to ask anybody else.

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:14.900
Okay?

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:17.990
But we also have this property of key rotation.

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:20.820
So, what happens when we want to rotate the key?

00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:22.420
So, the first thing we're going to do is we

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:25.470
're going to make a new document with our new key that

00:02:25.490 --> 00:02:27.960
we want to change, and we're going to sign it

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:28.810
with our old key.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:29.220
Okay?

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:31.990
And then, once we've done that, we can now

00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:35.100
sign all our future updates with the new key.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:40.830
And as far for normal key rotation, that means that it

00:02:40.830 --> 00:02:42.660
doesn't matter what happens to the old key.

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:42.990
Okay?

00:02:42.990 --> 00:02:44.720
We can leak that on the internet if we like.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:45.700
It doesn't matter.

00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:46.980
It's rotated out.

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:49.200
You do this because you no longer trust the old key.

00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:49.620
Okay?

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:51.410
So, that's what we've done.

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:54.570
The problem is, what happens if somebody does this?

00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:58.880
If somebody takes the old key, and they put an update

00:02:58.910 --> 00:03:00.990
chained on top of one of my early updates, and

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.450
they pretend that these later updates didn't happen.

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:04.870
Okay?

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:09.000
So, if you have this situation where somebody is in control

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.750
of one of your old keys, this is no longer self

00:03:11.750 --> 00:03:12.680
-authenticating.

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:13.040
Okay?

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:15.230
It's no longer self-authenticating because we did

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:16.100
key rotation.

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:21.230
So, we've got these kind of really different properties.

00:03:21.230 --> 00:03:24.980
Even though we all have dids, and they look the

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:28.980
same, different dids have really fundamentally different security properties.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:32.440
Some dids, your initial document is self-authent

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:34.330
icating a content address.

00:03:34.470 --> 00:03:35.090
Okay?

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:39.530
The one that you then updated is also self-authent

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:40.570
icating.

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:41.310
Okay?

00:03:41.310 --> 00:03:45.410
Right down at the other end, if you've rotated your

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.730
key and the earlier key has leaked, then this is not

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:50.940
at all self-authenticating.

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:51.470
Okay?

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:54.590
And then in the middle, there's this situation that a

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:57.670
lot of people who have migrated their PDS are in,

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:01.750
where you have the key in your history, but that key

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:03.540
hasn't leaked.

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:03.820
Right?

00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:05.960
So, if you're on Blue Sky, you've probably

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:09.040
got their rotation key in your history, but that key,

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:10.340
as far as we know, is still secure.

00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:13.150
So, there is only one chain of your identity, but

00:04:13.150 --> 00:04:15.620
we don't know what will happen in future.

00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:18.650
So, this situation at the top is very, very blessed

00:04:18.770 --> 00:04:19.060
.

00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:19.300
Right?

00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:20.490
This is wonderful.

00:04:20.590 --> 00:04:24.590
This is just like, this has the same security as,

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.580
like, an IPFS hash or a Bitcoin or an Ethereum

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:31.620
address or, for example, a Nostra ID.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:33.710
So, if you run into, like, a Nost

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:36.790
ra enthusiast who is concerned about, like, I heard

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.430
about this central server that I'm going to talk to you

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:38.820
about.

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:42.180
You can tell them, if you are happy with the N

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:43.260
ostra feature set, right?

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:44.900
Because the way they do it in Nostra is just

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:46.170
don't do key rotation.

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:47.640
You just don't lose your key.

00:04:47.650 --> 00:04:50.100
If you're happy with the Nostra feature set,

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:52.800
you can have Nostra-style security with DIP

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:53.290
PLC.

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:54.010
Right?

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:58.720
But once you use this feature set, in certain circumstances that

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:00.910
are kind of out of our control, we then lose this

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:03.750
security property and we end up with kind of a really differently

00:05:03.750 --> 00:05:04.420
secured system.

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:06.970
So, right down at the bottom, we're not self

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:08.490
-authenticating.

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:11.370
We've got Sadako crawling out of our TV screens.

00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:12.410
Our DID is cursed.

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:16.390
We can no longer verify just by looking at it whether it

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:17.220
's correct or not.

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:17.460
Okay?

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:22.900
So, the solution in DIP PLC is to use

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:24.430
a trusted sequencer.

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:27.070
So, the job of a sequencer is to say,

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.730
this is when this update was published.

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:34.290
And since I know that this one was published earlier, I

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:38.050
then know that the evil one that we did later is invalid

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:38.340
.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:38.820
Right?

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:42.030
So, they can choose the canonical chain and the correct way

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:42.980
to resolve your ID.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:46.800
And there's another slightly confusing thing about the DIP PL

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:49.360
C system, which is that this server actually has two jobs

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:49.500
.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:51.860
And they're really, really different jobs and have kind of

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:53.410
really different properties.

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:55.490
So, it's a sequencer, but it's also

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:56.740
a data publisher.

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:00.740
And you didn't have to do these together, right?

00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:02.470
These are fundamentally different things.

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:03.840
They could have been...

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:04.960
They're different roles.

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.270
They could have been done differently.

00:06:06.270 --> 00:06:07.860
And they have really different implications.

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:08.410
Okay.

00:06:08.410 --> 00:06:12.100
So, what happens if this trusted server goes rogue?

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:13.700
And you might think, okay, why is it going to

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:14.260
go rogue?

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:17.760
I'll give you one example of what I mean by rogue

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:18.100
.

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:24.660
So, we had this issue in Turkey where there was a

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:29.490
legal proceeding in Turkey that said that Blue Sky had to ban

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:31.220
some Turkish dissidents.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:32.100
Okay?

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.940
And they didn't do this at the level of the directory

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:34.060
.

00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:35.900
They did this just at the level of their PDS.

00:06:35.900 --> 00:06:39.070
But what this shows us is these well-meaning people

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.200
, they are not in the tank for the prime minister of

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:42.780
Turkey.

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:43.300
Right?

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:46.340
But well-meaning people can have pressure put on them

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:48.650
to do things that they would not necessarily want to do.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:49.140
Okay?

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:50.570
Because they live in the real world.

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:53.500
If they didn't do that, they couldn't change planes

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:54.350
in Istanbul.

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:57.050
And potentially, for example, the Blue Sky app would be

00:06:57.050 --> 00:06:58.730
banned from the App Store, at the very least in Turkey

00:06:58.730 --> 00:06:59.970
and potentially everywhere else.

00:07:00.110 --> 00:07:00.250
Okay?

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:03.870
So, there's now a plan which, until today,

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:07.460
I thought was a good plan, to go with a separate

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:08.430
organization.

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:11.260
And just thinking about my own talk, I realize it may

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:12.400
not be a good plan.

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:15.200
To go with a separate organization that's going to run the

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:18.620
directory, there's going to be a board of trustworthy people

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:22.440
on this, you know, on this board in control of

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:23.050
it.

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:24.590
And they're genuinely, you know, as far as I

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:25.620
can tell, trustworthy people.

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:30.500
So, let's assume that we succeed in the task of

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:33.870
keeping psychopaths off this board, which is an unsolved

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:37.060
problem in, like, human governance, right?

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:39.750
So, generally, you know, the first generation may not

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:42.700
have psychopaths, but they seem to somehow get there.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:44.520
But let's assume that they're all honest, well-

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:46.740
meaning people, and they care about Proto.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:50.170
Let's look at a similar example.

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:54.100
Private universities in the United States have a kind of a similar

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:55.170
governance structure.

00:07:55.310 --> 00:07:57.350
And they're actually a really good case for this kind of

00:07:57.350 --> 00:07:58.420
governance structure.

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:01.350
So, if you're trying to govern a private university in

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:04.170
the US, you've got a bunch of alumni who really

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:05.870
care about the institution, right?

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:07.460
They really care about the school.

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:10.250
And if they don't care about that, they care about

00:08:10.250 --> 00:08:11.850
their own personal reputations.

00:08:11.850 --> 00:08:14.330
So, this is a really good case for this governance that

00:08:14.330 --> 00:08:16.560
we're doing with PLC directory.

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:21.780
But what happened was that the Trump administration put pressure on them

00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:24.770
and took a bunch of things that they cared about hostage,

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:25.330
right?

00:08:25.450 --> 00:08:26.900
So, they said, "If you don't do the

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:29.090
things that we want, that we don't normally have the

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:32.770
rights to make you do, we are going to cancel grants

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:35.850
that your researchers are due.

00:08:35.950 --> 00:08:40.830
We're going to cancel the visas of overseas students at your

00:08:40.830 --> 00:08:44.630
university." So, these people were put in this dilemma where

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:49.130
they can have the policies that they think they can have,

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:50.980
or they can compromise.

00:08:50.980 --> 00:08:53.830
And if they compromise, then they're going to end up

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:56.480
hurting far fewer people than if they do what they're being

00:08:56.510 --> 00:08:57.140
told to do.

00:08:57.140 --> 00:08:59.900
So, ultimately, what, for example, Columbia and a

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:03.910
lot of other universities did was they threw trans people and Palestine

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:07.940
protesters under the bus to protect the majority of their institution,

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:08.740
okay?

00:09:08.740 --> 00:09:12.170
So, if you think about this with AppProto,

00:09:12.220 --> 00:09:14.420
if you care about AppProto, there are all kinds

00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:16.570
of ways that people can put pressure on you, right?

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.460
Can you get AppProto apps into the App Store?

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:22.020
Are you going to have network level blocks of the PLC

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:22.870
directory?

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:26.800
All kinds of things that you could do that will potentially put

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:30.700
a dilemma on the people who are governing this structure, even

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:33.060
if they're well-meaning people, and cause them

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:35.760
to do something that we may not think is what the social

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:37.300
contract would tell them to do, okay?

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:39.460
So, let's assume they go rogue.

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:42.010
Can we just do things?

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:44.930
Because I've got my client, right?

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:46.580
It's free software.

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:47.460
We've got our relays.

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:48.660
We know anybody can run the relays.

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:49.940
We've got our own PDSs.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.930
There's nothing that says that we have to look at the

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:53.370
PLC directory.

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:54.970
We can do what we like.

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:57.890
So, if I've got a self-authentic

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:00.180
did, this is probably actually okay.

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:01.690
So, here's what we can do.

00:10:01.690 --> 00:10:04.260
Somebody can set up the too hot for PLC directory.

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:08.170
The records that are being messed with by the PLC directory

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:10.060
, what we can do is we can query the PLC

00:10:10.110 --> 00:10:10.260
directory.

00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:13.550
We can look at our own data, and if the PL

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:19.620
C directory refuses to answer for that record or if it's

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:21.880
done some weird -- well, no, if it's refusing

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:24.210
to answer or if it's not giving us the whole chain

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:27.610
of updates that we've got, then we can just serve

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:29.540
what we've got, okay?

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:33.280
And the great thing about this is we don't really need

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:35.350
consensus to do this, right?

00:10:35.350 --> 00:10:40.120
We can have, like, bitterly, mutually detesting

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:43.990
factions of that proto, and you can make your directory and

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:46.620
I can make my directory, but since this is self-

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:49.160
authentic data we're looking at, we're ultimately

00:10:49.170 --> 00:10:51.490
all going to get to the same result, right?

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:53.110
As long as we share the data, we can all get

00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:53.930
to the same result.

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:56.900
So, we have this property that we wanted.

00:10:56.900 --> 00:10:59.130
I don't know if we still have strong consistency.

00:10:59.130 --> 00:10:59.910
I think we do.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:04.100
The problem is, okay, what about the sequencing part?

00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:07.600
Because the sequencing part is something where only the directory is allowed

00:11:07.600 --> 00:11:09.380
to make a decision, right?

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:12.980
And so, the sequencing -- it's making a decision about

00:11:12.980 --> 00:11:15.300
what time did I receive this update?

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:19.790
And somebody else may honestly get that update at a different time

00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:20.020
.

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:23.860
So, sequencing requires us to just have this single directory,

00:11:23.860 --> 00:11:25.220
and that's why it's designed like this, okay?

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:28.350
So, we can do things, but we all need to

