you can diagnose the problem." And it's like eight ter

00:17:14.820 --> 00:17:16.780
abytes of just irrelevant log files, you know?

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:18.010
They've got all the cards here.

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:20.260
Another thing they can do is they can spam the mirrors to

00:17:20.340 --> 00:17:24.200
death because one of the amazing things about this system is that

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:27.110
it's designed to kind of hold infinity records.

00:17:27.110 --> 00:17:29.870
Like, there's no cost to writing to it.

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:33.100
The only limitation on putting loads of stuff in the PLC

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:36.060
directory is that the operator is doing some rate limiting on,

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:37.940
like, IPs and PDSs and stuff like that

00:17:37.940 --> 00:17:38.110
.

00:17:38.110 --> 00:17:40.400
But in theory, as far as I know, everything is

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:41.780
supposed to go in there.

00:17:42.010 --> 00:17:44.880
So, they can allow other people spam in there.

00:17:44.890 --> 00:17:47.920
They can turn off the rate limiting until the mirrors fall over

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:48.080
.

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:49.820
They can also create their own spam.

00:17:49.830 --> 00:17:52.580
And the great thing about creating your own spam is you can

00:17:52.580 --> 00:17:55.160
do this deterministically from a secret seed.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:17:57.910
The mirrors have to hold all the data to have a complete

00:17:57.940 --> 00:17:58.240
set.

00:17:58.240 --> 00:17:59.880
You don't even have to hold the data.

00:17:59.880 --> 00:18:02.160
All you need is your seed and a serial number, and

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:03.330
you can serve it.

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:06.090
So, they've got all the cards when it comes to

00:18:06.090 --> 00:18:08.860
, like, spamming the mirrors and just making it impossible

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:10.180
for people to hold them accountable.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:12.250
Okay.

00:18:12.250 --> 00:18:14.080
So, what can we do to mitigate this?

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:16.150
I should be clear these aren't quite solutions, but they

00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:16.730
will help.

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:20.270
So, we can run lots of mirrors, right?

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:23.680
And this is something that's already, like, already happening

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:24.580
a little bit.

00:18:25.220 --> 00:18:28.650
So, we can – when we write, instead of writing

00:18:28.700 --> 00:18:31.300
to the PLC directory, we can write to the mirror

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:34.820
and have the mirror keep a log and share what they write

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.900
, and then forward that on to the directory.

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:39.170
So, that way, if the directory isn't giving us

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:42.420
all its data, we should still kind of maybe be able

00:18:42.420 --> 00:18:43.860
to piece some of it together.

00:18:43.860 --> 00:18:47.560
Try to get consensus on what the mirrors are actually showing us

00:18:47.690 --> 00:18:47.940
.

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:50.930
So, if the mirroring stops working on a Friday,

00:18:51.070 --> 00:18:53.460
we want also – we at least want to know that as

00:18:53.460 --> 00:18:55.300
of Thursday, we all know what it should be showing.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:57.940
There's then some technical things that I'll come to.

