00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:42.900
We can all tell that we've got the same mirror quite

00:22:42.900 --> 00:22:43.590
easily.

00:22:43.590 --> 00:22:46.510
We can quite easily sync up on the same thing.

00:22:46.570 --> 00:22:49.080
And we've got like a log of the history of what

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:51.130
the sequence actually sequenced.

00:22:51.130 --> 00:22:53.060
So, this is really important.

00:22:53.080 --> 00:22:58.360
We can have loads of people with like very lightweight devices ver

00:22:58.390 --> 00:23:01.700
ifying that that log is being appended to and not like

00:23:01.700 --> 00:23:03.410
reorg, as I understand it.

00:23:03.410 --> 00:23:06.310
And we can also have people run monitors who check that the

00:23:06.310 --> 00:23:08.660
rules are actually correctly applied.

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:11.700
So, this is already great and it will really help.

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:15.600
Ideally, we will push this as far down the stack as

00:23:15.720 --> 00:23:16.950
we possibly can.

00:23:16.980 --> 00:23:20.980
So, ideally, if the directory stops cooperating with the

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.400
system, we want stuff to break.

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:28.820
But this is the problem of having this kind of single position

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:30.020
of authority.

00:23:30.020 --> 00:23:32.310
They've got the official organization.

00:23:32.310 --> 00:23:34.690
They've got the single right privileges.

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:37.900
The problem with this is they have the ability to just kind

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:39.620
of turn that stuff off, right?

00:23:39.620 --> 00:23:41.590
Because if you're a developer, you know, you've

00:23:41.590 --> 00:23:44.260
got a choice between no records and invalid records.

00:23:44.260 --> 00:23:46.000
What are you going to do, right?

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:49.310
Unless we can really, really quickly coordinate this flag and move

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:51.050
to a new directory.

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:54.610
And this is the difference with how certificate transparency works with certificate

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:55.860
authorities, right?

00:23:55.880 --> 00:24:00.850
With like certificate transparency for SSL certificates.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:05.230
Because there, if you have a bad certificate authority that refuses

00:24:05.230 --> 00:24:10.260
to participate in the or breaks its participation in the scheme,

00:24:10.260 --> 00:24:14.140
which apparently does sometimes happen, your users can always get a

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:16.570
certificate from another authority.

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:19.360
But this is specifically the power that we don't have,

00:24:19.360 --> 00:24:21.300
at least in protocol in this system.

00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:23.910
You cannot move sequencer in didplc.

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:27.730
All we can do is try to coordinate this incredible flag day

00:24:27.730 --> 00:24:28.000
.

00:24:28.030 --> 00:24:33.960
There's a proposal a while back by Nick, who's

00:24:34.200 --> 00:24:38.330
someone you know, to make it possible to choose your directory

00:24:38.330 --> 00:24:38.650
.

00:24:38.750 --> 00:24:41.690
I don't think this allows you to escape from a bad

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:44.270
directory, but I think it potentially really helps.

00:24:44.340 --> 00:24:48.530
So that instead of having this single privileged position of the did

00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:51.700
plc directory that is in charge of didplc,

00:24:52.500 --> 00:24:54.260
you potentially have a bunch of different operators.

00:24:54.260 --> 00:24:55.700
So I really like this.

00:24:55.700 --> 00:24:58.720
And then, finally, I'm going to talk about some

00:24:58.720 --> 00:25:00.660
decentralized consensus approaches.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:07.910
So there are two serious problems with decentralized consensus for this application

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:10.340
and for a lot of approach applications.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:14.960
The first is that, like, in the American culture wars

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:16.730
, everything must have a side.

00:25:16.730 --> 00:25:20.010
And apparently, like, an open validator set is MA

00:25:20.010 --> 00:25:22.170
GA-coded nowadays, right?

00:25:22.170 --> 00:25:25.490
So, like, you can't say blockchain.

00:25:25.490 --> 00:25:28.700
You know, you have to kind of reinvent blockchain but not

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:29.700
tell people.

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:32.320
So there's that problem.

00:25:32.350 --> 00:25:37.130
And then the other problem is writing to a decentralized ledger

00:25:37.180 --> 00:25:39.450
generally costs you money.

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:43.150
And the reason why it costs you money is because it needs

00:25:43.150 --> 00:25:44.900
to somehow manage spam, right?

00:25:44.900 --> 00:25:49.940
So if you don't want to put anybody in charge of

00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:54.600
deciding what is a legitimate transaction, and also if you want

00:25:54.600 --> 00:26:00.330
to preserve the ability to mirror the entire dataset, then the

00:26:00.380 --> 00:26:05.410
only way I think that anybody knows is to charge money to

00:26:05.410 --> 00:26:05.860
write.

00:26:05.860 --> 00:26:08.730
So a couple of approaches.

00:26:08.740 --> 00:26:13.480
Well, there's a BFT system that somebody wrote.

00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:16.570
I think a lot of this stuff could probably be rewritten

00:26:16.570 --> 00:26:18.160
in the light of T-logs.

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:20.940
But there's a BFT suggestion using Comet BFT

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:21.300
.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:23.580
I haven't looked very hard at it, but it's

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:24.900
maybe interesting.

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:27.380
A couple of ideas by me.

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:30.570
The idea here is if we're going to use a blockchain

00:26:30.570 --> 00:26:33.400
, we want to have to avoid writing to it all the

00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:34.090
time.

00:26:34.090 --> 00:26:37.570
And we especially want to avoid regular users having to write to

00:26:37.710 --> 00:26:37.930
it.

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:39.250
So a couple of things.

00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:40.660
P2P guardrails.

00:26:40.660 --> 00:26:43.160
This is a suggestion where, firstly, you can change your

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:43.860
sequencer.

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:46.580
So if the directory is bad, you can escape.

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:51.060
Secondly, if the sequencer refuses to sequence something for you

00:26:51.060 --> 00:26:53.540
, then you or somebody on your behalf can send it to

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:55.620
the blockchain and we can read it off there.

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:59.880
And finally, we do some reorg protection based on kind

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:02.320
of T-log-like checksums so that you can

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:05.970
prove that you previously had something already accepted and that it shouldn

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:06.730
't be reorg'd.

00:27:06.740 --> 00:27:10.380
And then finally, this one, didcow.

00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:13.860
This is a proposal for a new kind of did.

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:18.370
And actually, what set me thinking about this was I saw

00:27:18.700 --> 00:27:22.790
that people are trying to do organizational control of dids.

00:27:22.860 --> 00:27:26.730
So, for example, you've got a decentralized organization,

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:29.060
you've got a bunch of different people, and they all

00:27:29.060 --> 00:27:32.400
want to share control in some way of a did.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.390
And this is something that some of the blockchain tooling does really

00:27:35.390 --> 00:27:36.020
, really well.

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:38.130
So I thought it would be useful if you had kind of

00:27:38.270 --> 00:27:43.220
an explicitly kind of blockchain oriented way of doing this.

00:27:43.220 --> 00:27:47.060
And the proposal is very simply, you make an ID with

00:27:47.060 --> 00:27:50.820
the controller blockchain address that wraps your regular ID.

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:54.980
You don't have to do a blockchain transaction to write this

00:27:54.980 --> 00:27:57.490
because if there's nothing on the blockchain, we're just

00:27:57.540 --> 00:27:59.620
going to use the thing that was in your address.

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:04.520
And then if you want to move your wrapped ID, let

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:07.330
's say you lose trust in did PLC, or you

00:28:07.480 --> 00:28:09.410
want to move from a cursed PLC entry to a non

00:28:09.410 --> 00:28:11.360
-cursed one, or you want to move to a

00:28:11.360 --> 00:28:14.170
did web or a different did web, whatever you want to

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:17.660
do, you can repoint this one with a blockchain transaction

00:28:17.760 --> 00:28:17.920
.

00:28:18.740 --> 00:28:20.520
Okay, so that's all I got.

00:28:20.520 --> 00:28:23.860
I've put links for all the technical things I talked about

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:26.600
up here, and I've also pinned this to my profile

00:28:26.610 --> 00:28:28.340
on GoatNavy on Blue Sky.

00:28:28.340 --> 00:28:30.370
That clock says one minute, but we actually have a couple

00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:30.820
of minutes.

00:28:30.900 --> 00:28:32.410
So do we have any questions?

00:28:32.420 --> 00:28:34.760
And actually, no, first, thank you.

00:28:34.790 --> 00:28:35.780
This was amazing.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:42.580
Okay.

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:49.260
So why don't we just all use did webs and then

00:28:49.310 --> 00:28:54.560
push the fight to the DNS layer?

00:28:54.580 --> 00:28:55.460
Yeah.

00:28:55.460 --> 00:28:58.440
If you'd asked me that a year ago, I would

00:28:58.440 --> 00:29:00.740
have said we should all use did webs.

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:08.030
But at that time, I had very naive assumptions about the

00:29:08.060 --> 00:29:13.520
nation state governed liberal institutions like, with a did web,

00:29:13.560 --> 00:29:16.690
everything is under a registrar, which is under a nation

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:17.250
state.

00:29:17.250 --> 00:29:19.970
And it seems like nation states will turn to fascism even

00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:22.580
within like a three year time span or something.

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:25.900
So I don't feel like that confident, like having a

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:28.330
did web for the next 20 years.

00:29:28.430 --> 00:29:30.940
If it was five years, I'm kind of cool with

00:29:30.940 --> 00:29:31.890
the did web.

00:29:32.030 --> 00:29:32.700
So yeah.

00:29:32.700 --> 00:29:35.570
So I think for long term, there's that.

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:38.550
And then the practical problem with did web is just that people

00:29:38.550 --> 00:29:42.030
have a hard time not losing their control of their own of

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:43.400
their domain.

00:29:43.430 --> 00:29:47.140
And also that the registrar will keep putting the price up

00:29:47.140 --> 00:29:48.060
with the domain as well.

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:50.500
Hi.

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:53.850
Thank you for all of the list of things we can do

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:54.980
to screw everybody over.

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:56.630
No.

00:29:56.730 --> 00:29:58.890
Okay.

00:29:59.070 --> 00:29:59.650
Seriously.

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:02.100
Speaking of my personal capacity.

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:02.820
But okay.

00:30:02.840 --> 00:30:04.550
So homework.

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:09.620
Sounds like we should make the policies for what is and isn

00:30:09.620 --> 00:30:14.020
't going to go in explicit so they will bind us for

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:14.500
the future.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:15.860
Yes.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:17.860
We should like Tlogs are good.

00:30:17.860 --> 00:30:19.090
I saw here.

00:30:19.090 --> 00:30:24.960
And maybe considered Tlog witnesses, Tlog mirrors, T

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:25.860
log monitors.

00:30:25.860 --> 00:30:28.850
Well monitors are permissionless.

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:29.470
But witnesses.

00:30:29.530 --> 00:30:30.100
Anything else?

00:30:30.100 --> 00:30:30.900
Right.

00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:34.900
So apart from kind of changing the whole system.

00:30:34.900 --> 00:30:42.900
Actually, one thing that occurred to me the other day was

00:30:42.920 --> 00:30:49.560
it would make more sense to separate out the reading and the

00:30:49.630 --> 00:30:50.150
sequencing.

00:30:50.250 --> 00:30:50.730
Right?

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:53.410
So if you are writing that Tlog, you don't

00:30:53.410 --> 00:30:56.180
necessarily need to be running the directory.

00:30:56.330 --> 00:30:57.860
Does that make sense?

00:30:57.860 --> 00:30:58.090
Right?

00:30:58.100 --> 00:31:01.090
You need your own version of the directory and you give proof

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:03.130
s to people when they asked to write to it.

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:05.780
But anybody could be running those directories.

00:31:05.780 --> 00:31:09.060
And I think it would be really useful if we could just

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:12.030
avoid this social point of like the PLC directory, which

00:31:12.200 --> 00:31:15.460
is clearly like the dictator of all things PLC.

00:31:16.820 --> 00:31:17.870
That would really help.

00:31:17.870 --> 00:31:20.500
So like at least potentially, you know, maybe have different

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:21.140
organizations.

00:31:21.140 --> 00:31:23.980
Maybe Blue Sky should keep PLC directory and you should just

00:31:23.980 --> 00:31:26.180
do sequencing at the non-profit.

00:31:26.180 --> 00:31:28.660
And the non-sequencing part here is just a read

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:32.260
-only service that makes things available.

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:32.730
Is that right?

00:31:32.740 --> 00:31:34.950
Well, actually, I mean, there's a couple of

00:31:34.950 --> 00:31:35.730
ways to do it.

00:31:35.870 --> 00:31:37.680
One way to do it would be just to do timestamps

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:37.700
.

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:40.880
So you would literally get a message and say, "What

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:43.300
time did I give you this message?" And then you give

00:31:43.300 --> 00:31:45.170
it back to them with a signature.

00:31:45.170 --> 00:31:48.290
But I think you could do something similar with the T log

00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:50.100
, like some feature of T logs.

00:31:50.100 --> 00:31:52.600
Yeah, I think the T log equivalent is a read-

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:55.990
only replica, which can also choose to the set of witnesses

00:31:55.990 --> 00:31:57.040
that signed that T log.

00:31:57.040 --> 00:31:58.820
But that can be done permissionlessly.

00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:00.740
Like anybody can spin one of those up downstream.

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:03.540
Anybody can spring up a mirror.

00:32:03.540 --> 00:32:08.880
But what I want to communicate here is that the switching over

00:32:09.080 --> 00:32:11.210
from the PLC, like the PLC, it's

00:32:11.260 --> 00:32:14.190
a social arrangement, just as much as a technical arrangement,

00:32:14.190 --> 00:32:14.260
right?

00:32:14.260 --> 00:32:18.500
So who do people think runs the PLC?

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:22.020
And this is why earlier I said, like, until I

00:32:22.020 --> 00:32:24.070
was practicing this talk, I thought it was a good idea

00:32:24.070 --> 00:32:25.380
to move to a new organization.

00:32:25.380 --> 00:32:28.940
And now I don't, because the new organization will actually

00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:31.620
have much more authority than the old organization.

00:32:31.620 --> 00:32:35.040
Like, if I look at those really good social recovery operations

00:32:35.060 --> 00:32:37.780
, they're all against some evil corporation.

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:41.620
So we can we can totally paint blue sky as an evil

00:32:41.620 --> 00:32:46.670
corporation, and like organize this social recovery to foil their evil

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:47.180
plans.

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:50.180
But like with a Swiss organization that's, you know,

00:32:50.180 --> 00:32:50.980
it's...

00:32:50.980 --> 00:32:54.890
Worse reputation is that better.

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:57.980
You have to wear, you have to wear hoods with

00:32:58.030 --> 00:32:59.590
the robes with hoods, basically.

00:32:59.590 --> 00:33:00.730
And then yeah, okay.

00:33:00.730 --> 00:33:01.850
Let's take two more.

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:03.460
Anybody else?

00:33:03.460 --> 00:33:07.240
Well, this is maybe going into the weeds a bit too

00:33:07.240 --> 00:33:07.890
much.

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:11.000
But I'm curious why the did cow proposal didn't have

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.740
included chain ID, if I understand correctly, the address is

00:33:13.740 --> 00:33:14.820
a smart contract.

00:33:14.820 --> 00:33:15.380
That's correct.

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:18.660
The reason why it didn't include a chain ID was big

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:19.460
was two reasons.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:21.690
Firstly, it's already quite long.

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:27.310
And secondly, the big burden, I think actually, of

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:30.610
those two proposals, and also probably the reason why the guard

00:33:30.610 --> 00:33:33.480
rails proposal is actually obviously dead in the water, is

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:36.790
that you need a, you need an RPC endpoint,

00:33:36.790 --> 00:33:37.620
right?

00:33:37.620 --> 00:33:39.570
You need a connection to the block, a reconnection to

00:33:39.570 --> 00:33:41.140
the blockchain to resolve anything.

00:33:41.140 --> 00:33:45.030
So if we have lots of other chains there, then whoever

00:33:45.030 --> 00:33:47.740
is resolving this has got to have lots of different working R

00:33:47.740 --> 00:33:48.820
PC endpoints.

00:33:48.840 --> 00:33:49.870
So I'm kind of like, okay, what's the

00:33:49.870 --> 00:33:50.820
simplest thing that could work?

00:33:50.820 --> 00:33:53.620
You know, one RPC, no chain ID.

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:56.180
Okay.

